The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps the entire `System.IO` surface.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```bash
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));

manager.Save("/output.json", "data");
Assert.Equal("data", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/output.json"));

Assert.False(mockFs.Directory.Exists("/nonexistent"));
```

**Key points:**
- Your three statics (`File.ReadAllText`, `File.WriteAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) all become calls on `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*` — same API, just on the injected instance.
- `MockFileSystem` gives you a fully in-memory filesystem for tests — no temp files, no cleanup.
- Register as `AddSingleton` since `FileSystem` is stateless.

If you want help bulk-migrating all the existing call sites to use `IFileSystem`, I can do that too — just point me at the project.
